                <td height="622" valign="top" colspan="2" bgcolor="#004142">&nbsp;<table width="100%" border="0" cellpadding="4"><tr bgcolor="#000000"><td><font color="#FFFFFF"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial" size="6">What makes a good tournament player</font></td></tr></table><table width="100%" border="0" cellpadding="4" cellspacing="0"><tr><td></td><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Rating</Font></TD><TD><IMG SRC="images/a5.gif" BORDER=0><A HREF="articleread.php3?article=45"><IMG SRC="images/aread.GIF" BORDER=0></A><A HREF="articlereview.php3?article=45"><IMG SRC="images/areview.GIF" BORDER=0></A></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Author</Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2"><A HREF="../membercenter/directory/memberpage.php3?member=29">Michael "rayc" Hawley</A></FONT></TD></TR><!-- 29 --><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Description</Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2">A look at some of the more important qualities that make a good SWCCG tournament player. This is a re-post of an article from a previous newsletter.</FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Article</Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2">First let's define our terms. What is meant by a 'good tournament player?' Given the focus of the DeckTech newsletter, I assume that 'good tournament player' means a player who wins or finishes in the top few players at most of the tournaments he or she enters. While I will focus on the characteristics that help players win, I have to say that winning does not make you a 'good tournament player.' I am tempted to rant about sportsmanship here ... consider yourself ranted at.<br>
<br>
There are two general qualities that make a winning tournament player -- preparedness and presence of mind. I'll address preparedness first.<br>
<br>
Deck building:<br>
Deck building is the obvious part of preparedness. A winning player is aware of what deck types are available and popular and can adapt a deck to suit his/her own style of play and to respond to the types of decks he/she is likely to play. A really good player will have some element of surprise or uniqueness to his/her decks which make them challenging for even an experienced opponent.<br>
<br>
Knowledge of the cards:<br>
Knowledge of the cards gives you the universe of possibilities. Obviously this will help with your deck building. Is there a card that achieves your goal, which is more efficient or has a higher destiny than the one you saw in that deck posting? The better your knowledge of the cards the better your chances of making good choices. It will also give you a better idea of what to worry about during the game.<br>
<br>
Knowledge of the rules:<br>
This sounds trivial but we all know that the rules are not simple nor are they intuitive. Often, when I add a new strategy to a deck, I E-mail the tournament director to get an advance ruling and confirm the ruling in<br>
person on the day of the tournament.<br>
<br>
Knowledge of local trends:<br>
What decks/cards to people play/fear. What is the local approach to SAC and Grimnok. Local trends are of supreme importance. I play in Kashyyk, which deck-wise is a bit of a backwater. A while back, when the JP Manipulator deck took the world by storm, nobody played it around here. I'm not sure why. But, if you were watching the web sites, you would have built one of the many anti-manipulator decks and been in for a big surprise when you started with the Throne Room and the dark side started with the Death Star.<br>
<br>
Next I will address presence of mind. Presence of mind is what makes the difference in a game where the decks are well matched and neither player has overwhelmingly good or bad luck. It keeps a player from losing due to avoidable factors. It expands winning differentials and trims losing differentials.<br>
<br>
Adaptability:<br>
The best players can respond to a game that has not unfolded according to plan. They can spot a weakness in the opponents deployment and exploit it.<br>
<br>
Focus:<br>
I think the most important thing for a tournament player to remember is to be in the game at all times. Concentration is the hallmark of the very best players. A great player will often be able to tell you his/her destiny numbers before drawing them -- and then tell you yours! Good players count their cards and track their destinies. They don't let their opponents switch from one phase to another without giving them an opportunity to play a card or perform an action. They don't forget anything.<br>
<br>
Tenacity:<br>
It is very important to play each game to the finish. There is something to be learned even in a humiliating defeat. Good players don't concede defeat until defeat is inevitable. Even then they look for ways to minimize the damage. They also continue to size up their opponents deck to see if there are ways to counter it that they hadn't thought of. Contrariwise, a great player never relaxes his grip on a worthy opponent. There is always a danger that an opponent will mount an unexpected comeback. That said, (sportsmanship rant warning!!!) it is important not to rub your opponent's face in it. I consider it a sign of respect for my opponent to treat me as potentially dangerous even when I am down. I am an adult and I have confidence in my abilities. A good player gives the newer, younger, or weaker players a break. If they seem receptive, a good player will talk strategy, make suggestions, answer their questions. I have been on the receiving end of this many times. I was fortunate to have been exposed to many decent players like this before I met up with my first egotistical newbie crusher.<br>
<br>
Anyway, those are some of my thoughts on what makes a good tournament player. I hope you can use them.<br>
<br>
</FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP" COLSPAN="2"><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2"><a href="articles.php3"><img src="images/aback.GIF" border="0"></a><A HREF="articleread.php3?article=45"><IMG SRC="images/aread.GIF" BORDER=0></A><A HREF="articlereview.php3?article=45"><IMG SRC="images/areview.GIF" BORDER=0></A><a href="articleprint.php3?article=45" TARGET="BLANK_"><img src="images/aprint.gif" border="0"></a></FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> </td>
